{{Infobox high court |court_name = Council of Luxembourg |native_name = Conseil de Luxembourg |image = |imagesize = |caption = |motto = |established = 1444 |dissolved = 1795 |country = [[Duchy of Luxembourg]] |location = [[Luxembourg (city)|Luxembourg]] |type = <!-- partisan election/non-partisan election/legislative selection/executive selection/co-option/etc --> |authority = <!-- constitution/statute/monarch--> |terms = <!-- length of court term for judges --> |positions = <!-- number of positions/seats on court --> }}
The '''Council of Luxembourg''' was the central institution in the government of the [[Duchy of Luxembourg]] from 1444 to 1795, in direct descent from the medieval council of the dukes. It was a body that had both administrative and judicial authority. The council was reorganized by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] in 1531–1532.<ref>R. Petit, "Keizerlijke verordening houdend reglement van de Raad van Luxemburg, 1532", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'' (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 132-141.</ref> Until 1782, legal decisions of the council could be appealed to the [[Great Council of Mechelen]]. On 1 August 1782 the council was made "sovereign", that is, the highest court in its jurisdiction.
The council was abolished on 7 June 1795.
